1. Preprocessing and vectorizaion.¶

1.1.1. Preprocessing (Bag-of-words presentation)¶

Transforming data to tidy format.

I start by transforming the data into a tidy format, where it seperate the words from the tweets and we do not care about the sequencing, which creates these "bag-of-words".

In [0]:
tweets_tidy <- twitter %>% 
  select(ID, class, tweet) %>%
  unnest_tokens(output = word, input = tweet)
In [9]:
head(tweets_tidy)

Above we can see that the words are seperated from the tweets.

Below I want to count the words

In [10]:
tweets_tidy %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% # Count "word". "sort = TRUE" means that it will sort the words in descending order of number words.

In the head, we can see that the most common word is "a" followed by "bitch" (:-D).

Allot of the words is stop words and meaningless words, fx "rt" which is just shortterm for "retweet".

Remove stop words and other meaningless words.

I want to filter out stop words, where I use the stop_words lexicon from tidytext. Also I want to define some own stop words from the head, that I does not expect to be a part of the stop words lexicon.

In [0]:
own_stopwords <- tibble(word= c("rt", "http", "t.co", "amp"),
                        lexicon = "OWN")
In [0]:
tweets_tidy %<>% # I use "%<>%" which both assigns and pipe - instead of first assigning and then piping. 
  anti_join(stop_words %>% bind_rows(own_stopwords), by = "word") # I use anti_join instead of filter, because it should be a bit faster.

Remove non-Alphanumeric words & words with only one character.

Here I mutate (recreate) the word variable, by removing words with Alphanumeric characters using the "str_remove_all" function.

In same code, I also filter out words with a lenght at 1, by using the "str_length" function.

In [0]:
tweets_tidy %<>%
  mutate(word = word %>% str_remove_all("[^[:alnum:]]") ) %>% # alnum = Alphanumeric characters. 
  filter(str_length(word) > 1) # filter out words with 1 character.

Remove words with numbers.

I also want to remove the words with numbers and here I use the "gsub" function.

In [0]:
tweets_tidy %<>%
  mutate(word = trimws(gsub("[^\\s]*[0-9][^\\s]*", "", word, perl=T))) %>%
  filter(str_length(word) > 1) # this filter out the words that are blank.

**Remove words used several times from same user and in same tweet

Here I want to remove the words that the same user (ID) have used the word more than 1 times in his/her tweets, and also where the same user have tweeted more than fives.

Doing this, then the word count wont be highly affected by a user that for example have used the same word or tweeted extremely many times (which should probably make it more general).

In [0]:
tweets_tidy %<>%
  add_count(ID, word, name = "nword") %>%
  add_count(ID, name = "ntweet") %>%
  filter(nword > 1 & ntweet > 5) %>%
    select(-nword, -ntweet)

Checking the cleaned word counts.

Here I again count the number of times the different words have been used. Afterwards I also plot the top 20 most used words in the tweets.

1.1.3. Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA)¶

Here I use LSA topic modelling to reduce dimensions.

In [0]:
pacman::p_load(quanteda) # I load quanteda that contain the LSA function.

I start by creating a document features matrix, which I need for the LSA modelling.

In [0]:
tweets_dfm <- tweets_tidy %>%
  count(ID, word) %>%
  cast_dfm(document = ID, term = word, value = n)

Let us just check the documents features matrix with a wordcloud.

In [22]:
textplot_wordcloud(tweets_dfm)

Again we can see that "bitch" is the most represented word in the tweets.

Now I fit the LSA model by using "textmodel_lsa", where the only argument inside is the document features matrix.

In [0]:
tweets_lsa <- tweets_dfm %>%
  textmodel_lsa()

1.2. Train a word-embedding model (GloVe)¶

In [0]:
pacman::p_load(text2vec)
In [0]:
tweets_corpus <- twitter %>% corpus(docid_field = "ID", text_field = "tweet")
In [0]:
tweet_toks <- tokens(tweets_corpus, what = "word") %>%
  tokens_tolower() %>%
  tokens(remove_punct = TRUE, 
         remove_symbols = TRUE)

  dfm_trim(min_termfreq = 5) %>%
  featnames()

Overall the tweets are mostly classes as offensive language.

2.2. Identifying themes¶

2.2.1. Using topic model (LSA)¶

First I will use kmeans for clustering the LSA topic model.

In [0]:
kmeans_lsa <- kmeans(tweets_lsa_loading, centers = 3, nstart = 20) # I set centers to 3, because I expect the LSA to cluster by the 3 classes (perhaps)
In [0]:
tweets_lsa_loading2 <- tweets_lsa_loading %>%
  mutate(ID = as.double(ID)) %>%
  left_join(twitter, by = "ID") # I use left_join, so I merge the class coloumn into the LSA matrix.

Then I use a crosstabs with the classes from the LSA model in the rows and have the clusters at the coloumns. Here I will try to see if I can identify if any of the clusters are specific to the classes.

In [81]:
table(tweets_lsa_loading2$class, kmeans_lsa$cluster)

   
      1   2   3
  0  56  53  73
  1 928 908 618
  2 158 211 120

Well I cant really identify any clear clusters that are specific to the classes. This could might indicate that there are not such a big different in the word counts at the three classes.

Therefor I will try plot the must frequent words in the 3 classes below.

In [79]:
tweets_tidy %>%
  mutate(class = as.factor(class)) %>%
  count(class, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  group_by(class) %>%
  top_n(20) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  ggplot(aes(reorder_within(word, n, class), n,
    fill = class
  )) +
  geom_col(alpha = 0.8, show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_x_reordered() +
  coord_flip() +
  facet_wrap(~class, scales = "free") +
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0)) +
  labs(
    x = NULL, y = "Word count",
    title = "Most frequent words in the 3 classes",
    subtitle = "Words in class 0 and 1 seems pretty similar, and class 2 is also in some extent pretty similar"
  )

Selecting by n

Looking at the plots, it looks like class 0 (hate speech) and class 1 (offensive language), has many of the same words and therefor are maybe close to each other.

Also the class 2 (neither), has some of the common words as class 1 - fx gt, love, hoe/hoes, but has also alot more "neutral" words.

Cluster 1: The cluster with high tf & idf values, which indicate that this is the more uncommon words in the weets. In the crosstab earlier, this indicate that it is alot of the class 1 and 2 that is in here.

Cluster 2: The smallest cluster with low tf (low proportion of words in the tweets) & a high idf value (uncommon words in the tweets). This cluster did not have many hate speech and offensive language tweets, which probably is because it is uncommon words and they are not highly represented in the tweets.

Cluster 3: This has "medium" tf and a low idf value (most common words). Here hate speech and offensive language was highly represented, which is proably because of the the common words as fx bitch.

3. Build an ML model that can predict hate speech¶

In this section I am going to try create three classification models using the LSA model (I tried using the TD-IDF, but didnt worked and could not find a solution).

Add logical variable:

First I create a new variable "hate_speech" in the LSA matrix.

In [0]:
tweets_lsa_loading_ML <- tweets_lsa_loading2 %>%
  select(2:12) %>%
  mutate(hate_speech = as.logical(class==0, class)) # I set class == 0, so class 0 is TRUE and the rest FALSE:

Load caret and recipes package.

I load caret and recipes, which I need for the preprocessing and training the data.

In [0]:
pacman::p_load(caret, recipes)

Splitting the data into train- and test set.

In [0]:
index <- createDataPartition(y = tweets_lsa_loading_ML$hate_speech, p = 0.75, list = FALSE) # 75% to 25% split
training <- tweets_lsa_loading_ML[index,]
test <- tweets_lsa_loading_ML[-index,]

Preprocessing using the recipes package.

In [0]:
reci <- recipe(hate_speech ~ ., data = training) %>%
  step_center(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>% # Centers all numeric variables to mean = 0
  step_scale(all_numeric(), -all_outcomes()) %>% # this scales the numeric variables
  step_zv(all_predictors())  # Removed predictors with zero variance

reci %<>%
  prep(data = train)

Setting the x and y values

In [0]:
# Predictors
x_train <-bake(reci, new_data = training) %>% select(-hate_speech,-class) # I remove class from the predictors.
y_train <- training %>% pull(hate_speech) %>% as.factor()
# test: split in y and x
x_test <-bake(reci, new_data = test) %>% select(-hate_speech,-class)
y_test <- test %>% pull(hate_speech) %>% as.factor()

Setting the workflow

In [0]:
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv",
                     number = 4)
metric <- "Kappa" # I use Kappa because the class 0 (hate speech) is so low represented in the data.
In [119]:
install.packages('e1071', dependencies=TRUE)

3.4. Conclusion.¶

Apparently the decision three model is the only reasonable classification model to predict the hate speech and with a little engineering, the sensivity could maybe be a bit better.
